Final Example
class Animal{

    void sound(){

        System.out.println("Animal");

    }

}

class Dog extends Animal{

    void sound(){

        System.out.println("Dog");

    }

    void bark(){

        System.out.println("Bark");

    }

}

public class Main{

    public static void main(String[] args){

        Animal a = new Dog();

        a.sound();

        a.bark();

    }

}

Let's trace it together.

First line
a.sound();

Reference:

Animal

Animal has sound()?

✅ Yes.

Object:

Dog

Dog overrides sound()?

✅ Yes.

Output:

Dog
Second line
a.bark();

Reference:

Animal

Does Animal have bark()?

❌ No.

Java says:

Compile Error

The object (Dog) is never even checked because the reference type doesn't allow calling bark().

